frameDefinitions: An Entity is obscure, unnotable, and in general little-known.
In this frame Party_1 meets with Party_2 at a prearranged Time and Place.
Words in this frame have to do with a Cognizer believing that some Phenomenon will take place in the future.
An Entity is evaluated for whether or not it belongs to a particular Reference_category in a context where its category membership is doubtful.
A State_of_affairs is generally, or with regard to a particular Feature, representative of its class, which may be narrowed to a specific Comparison_set.
A person or group, the Authority, believes that another person, the Suspect is a participant in a criminal Incident.
frameExamples: Geoffrey Rush was <t>little</t> <t>known</t> outside his native Australia when he soared to international prominence.
I <t>met with</t> my professor to talk about my midterm.

It can be hard to get your money back after discovering you've bought a <t>bogus</t>
autograph for hundreds or thousands of dollars!
The Elan truly is an <t>unusual</t> car; the first and only Lotus with a front engined/front wheel drive layout, and the first new Lotus to be introduced since 1975.
The police <t>suspect</t> Noah Rogers of aiding the robbery last night at Shop-n-drive.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Entity</fen> which is not widely known and rather obscure.
The <fen>Time</fen> during which the <fen>Entity</fen> is not well known.
The location where the <fen>Entity</fen> is not famous.

<fen>Party_1</fen> is the grammatically more prominent participant in the meeting event.  It can refer to either a single individual or a larger party separate from <fen>Party_2</fen> before the meeting.
A grammatically less prominent participant in the meeting event.  It can refer to either a single individual or a larger party separate from <fen>Party_1</fen> before the meeting.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the meeting happens.
The <fen>Place</fen> where the meeting happens.

This is the person who believes some Phenomenon will take place in the future. It is normally expressed as an External Argument: <fex name='Cognizer'>Pat</fex> <t>expects</t> that the Yankees will win the World Series.

This is what the Cognizer believes will happen in the future. It can be expressed as a Finite Clause Complement, an NP Object, or a VP Complement with or without an NP Object (see General Grammatical Observations):
An entity that serves as the focus of a predicted <fen>Phenomenon</fen>.
The time when the <fen>Cognizer</fen> makes the prediction.
The location where the <fen>Cognizer</fen> foresees the <fen>Phenomenon</fen>.
The <fen>Entity</fen> that is being evaluated in terms of whether it is an instance of the <fen>Reference_category</fen>.
The type relative to which the <fen>Entity</fen> is evaluated.
The state of affairs which is evaluated with regard to whether it exhibits the essential characteristics of a Comparison_set.
A property of the <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> wherein it differs or is similar to members of a <fen>Comparison_set</fen>.
The <fen>Authority</fen> is the group or person who suspects the <fen>Suspect</fen> of criminal activity.
The <fen>Suspect</fen> is the target of the <fen>Authority</fen>'s suspicion.
The (typically criminal) <fen>Incident</fen> in which the <fen>Suspect</fen> is suspected of being involved.
When the suspecting takes place.
listRoleExamples: Certain academic works are obscure <fex>only in North America</fex>.
Pat expects <fex>that the Yankees will win the World Series</fex>.
Predictions <fex>about stock prices</fex> are notoriously undependable.
She predicted the outcry <fex>several months ago</fex>.
<fex>Even at the far side of the house</fex> I could predict what was going on the kitchen.
<fex>The bomb found at the US Embassy in Berlin</fex> was fake.
However I have always loved having an unusual <fex>name</fex> and I think it's a beautiful name. .
David Hasselhoff's daughters are normal <fex>in every way</fex>.
Jakobson was placed under suspicion <fex>last week</fex> .
